The paper focuses on test prioritization in dynamic programming languages, specifically using Python as an example. This suggests that the paper is likely to fall under the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of information retrieval techniques for prioritizing tests, which falls under the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) category. The paper also discusses the design of a tool for generating faulty changes and test results, which could fall under the Programming Languages (cs.PL) or Software Development (cs.SD) categories. Finally, the paper discusses the design of alternative retrieval models, which could fall under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category.
